ce:section.ce:para:
The new ruthenium nitrosyl complex Ru-NO was prepared starting from the tridentate TPYCOOH ligand, following a similar approach to our previous description (Scheme 2
                        ) [19,20]. The UV–vis spectra of Ru-NO in DMF shows relatively weak absorption compared with that of its precursor, Ru-Cl, in the visible region (Fig. 1A). The FT-IR spectra of Ru-NO displayed a peak at 1895cm−1, a characteristic stretching vibration assignable to NO; this peak is absent in the spectrum of Ru-Cl (Fig. 1B). Ru-NO and FA (mixed in a molar ratio of Ru-NO:FA=8:1) were then incorporated onto the surface of the CDs via an amide bond coupling of the amine-functionalized CDs and the carboxylic acid groups in Ru-NO or FA in the presence of EDC/NHS, thus forming the {Ru-NO@FA@CDs} nanoplatform (Scheme 1). The successful graft of Ru-NO to the CD surfaces was evidenced by FT-IR spectroscopy (Fig. 2A). The FT-IR spectrum of the bare CDs showed a strong peak at 1723cm−1, a characteristic stretching vibration of CO for the carboxyl groups in the CDs. This peak shifted to 1627cm−1 in CDs-NH2 after its surface was functionalized by ethylenediamine, suggesting the formation of an amide bond. The FT-IR spectrum of {Ru-NO@FA@CDs} revealed a peak at 1874cm−1, which was absent in that of CDs-NH2; this was assigned to the stretching vibration of NO (Fig. 2A). The obvious blue shift of ν
                        NO from 1895cm−1 in the uncoupled Ru-NO to 1874cm−1 in the {Ru-NO@FA@CDs} nanoplatform indicates the presence of covalently grafted Ru-NO on the surface of the CDs [19,20].
